defaultIssues with Current Situation of defaultAdministering and defaultManaging Land in Scotlanddefault&#xa0;
defaultFragmented Land Policies
default - 
defaultThere is no single source of land policy or National Land Policy – rather, the policies on land in Scotland are located in numerous sources such as national development policies, land use strategies, laws and regulations and even as the result of admini
defaultstrative practices. Also, there are numerous policies across the government directorates and agencies that touch on land, such as policies on housing, education, natural heritage, economic development, etc. This patchwork of land policies makes it problema
defaulttic for these land policies to collectively align and effectively support the vision for Scotland and ensure that land effectively supports Scotland’s future needs.
default&#xa0;
defaultWeak Land Governance
default - the governance arrangements of land
default are weak – there is no recognis
defaulted champion of the sector and no cross cutting government body of senior officials, such as a Land Commission, to co-ordinate land activities. This has resulted in weaknesses in two crucial areas: there is no overall National Land Policy, neither in genera
defaultl nor on the state and public lands in particular, providing a consistent policy framework of all the ministries managing land; and the lack of efficient co-ordination across the ministries involved in land administration and management significantly delay
defaults or stops the implementation of land 
defaultinitiatives
default, including land reform
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultInconsistent Management of Land
default - the institutional arrangements for administering and managing land are highly fragmented across 
defaultScottish
default public sector custodians and there is neit
defaulther regulatory nor executive oversight body. This results in inconsistent and inefficient approaches to land management.
default&#xa0;
defaultInefficient Land Information Management
default – information about land is captured, maintained and managed independently by the custodians o
defaultf land without the adoption of national data and procedural standards. This has resulted in land information being incomplete, inconsistent, inaccessible and not shared and used across Government
default and beyond
default. For example, there is no definitive inventory of
default state 
defaultand public 
defaultland
default and the geographic access to land ownership
default is limited to land within the Land R
defaultegister
default. 
