defaultA National Land Policy and associated Land Reform Policy must be evidence based. This will only happen if Scotland creates a National Land Information Se
defaultrvice that provides ease of access to a holistic set of interoperable land information about Scotland.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultLand Administration Systems provide the infrastructure for implementing land policies and land 
defaultmanagement strategies in support of sustainable development. This infrastructure includes the institutional arrangements, a legal framework, processes, standards, land information, management and dissemination systems, and technologies required to support 
defaultallocation, land markets, valuation, control of uses, and development of interests in land. Land Administration Systems are dynamic and evolve to reflect the people-to-land relationships, to adopt new technologies and to manage a wider and richer set of la
defaultnd information. The Registers of Scotland provide 
defaultthe 
defaultland tenure element of Scotland’s Land Administration System.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;defaultFigure 1: The land management paradigm (5)defaultLand management underpins the distribution and management of a key asset of any society namely
default its land. For western democracies, with their highly geared economies, land management is a key activity of both government and the private sector. Land management, and especially the central land administration component, aim to deliver efficient land ma
defaultrkets and effective management of the use of land in support of economic, social, and environmental sustainability. The land management paradigm, as illustrated in Figure 1, allows everyone to understand the role of the land administration functions (land 
defaulttenure, land value, land use, and land development) and how land administration institutions relate to the historical circumstances of a country and its policy decisions. The 
defaultLand Administration System
default is the fundamental infrastructure that underpins and i
defaultntegrates the land tenure, land value, land use and land development functions of land administration to support an efficient land market that fully demonstrates sustainable development.
default&#xa0;
defaultLand Administration Systems are just a means of implementing land po
defaultlicies. However, Scotland does not have a National Land Policy to provide a holistic framework to guide the land tenure, land value, land use and land development functions of land administration. It is recommended that Scotland creates a National Land Pol
defaulticy to guide the future of 
defaultScottish land 
defaultinstitutions
default, including the land reform agenda.
default 
defaultAn example framework for a National Land Policy is detailed in Appendix A.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultLand administration and management in Scotland is characterised by the fragmentation of responsibilities across a wide range of land custodians with little monitoring and regulation of their land activities. This 
defaultlaissez faire
default custodian approach is contrar
defaulty to international good practice that is increasingly integrating and regulating the management of state and public land. For example, Singapore has formed a Singapore Land Authority that integrates land registration and cadastre, state land management, ge
defaultospatial and land information management, corporate services and regulation. It is therefore recommended that land institutional arrangements in 
defaultScotland
default are incrementally integrated over the following transitional steps.
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLand Coordination Committee
defaultThe first step change in strengthening the governance of land in 
defaultScotland
default would be to create a Land Coordination Committee, reporting to 
defaulta Minister
default, composed of senior officials from the key 
defaultdirectorates
default 
defaultand agencies
default managing 
defaultand administering
default land. This L
defaultand Coordination Committee would have responsibilities at both the policy and operational levels. A key activity will be to create impro
defaultved access to integrated land information.
default&#xa0;
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLand Commission
defaultOnce the Land Coordination Committee is operating effectivel
defaulty, then the land governance could be further strengthened by transforming the Land Coordination Committee (based purely on cooperation) into a Land Commission with 
defaultformalis
defaulted executive roles and responsibilities. As well as continuing the role of coordinat
defaulting land activities, a key responsibility for the Land Commission would be 
defaultformulating and maintaining a National Land Policy and monitoring that the individual 
defaultdirectorates’ and agencies’
default policies are aligned and implementing the National Land Policy. This will ensure the allocation of rights to use the land delivers sustainable development and provides optim
defaultum social and economic benefits
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLand Authority
defaultIn the medium term institutional 
defaultreform in the land sector should go further and consolidate many of the current land administration and management activities of the diverse 
defaultdirectorates and agencies
default, including mapping and geospatial information management, into a single Land Authority. T
defaulthis would be similar to the institutional solutions introduced into New Zealand (
defaulthttp://www.linz.govt.nz/
default ) and Singapore (
defaulthttp://www.sla.gov.sg/
default ). 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultScottish public sector professionals tend to be specialists in narrow fields in the land sector and are missing the wider land management perspective and understanding. This reduces the professionals’ interest and involvement in wider land policy iss
defaultues and coordination of land activities across directorates and agencies. It is recommended that capacity building programmes be identified and designed, e.g. continued professional development training programmes, establish a post-graduate educational pro
defaultgram on land management in cooperation with Scottish Universities. Capacity building programmes are a continuous process and should be activated as soon as possible to ensure that the resources are available to underpin the recommended improvements in land
default administration and management in Scotland.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultDevelopment practitioners of all persuasion recognize that a well-functioning land sector can boost a country's economic growth, foster social development, shiel
defaultd the rights of vulnerable groups and help with environmental protection. Improving practices requires an objective assessment of the land governance setting, and the identification of priority areas.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe 
defaultLand Governance Assessment Framework (
defaultLGAF
default)
default, 
defaultdeveloped by the World Bank and its partners, provides a holistic, diagnostic review at the country level that can inform policy dialogue in a clear and targeted manner. It is built around five main areas for policy intervention:
default&#xa0;
defaulta)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLegal and institutional f
defaultramework
defaultb)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLand use planning, management and taxation
defaultc)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultManagement of public land
defaultd)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultPublic provision of land information
defaulte)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDispute resolution and conflict management
default&#xa0;
defaultThe LGAF helps policymakers and other stakeholders to make sense of the technical levels of the 
defaultland sector, benchmark governance, prioritize reforms in the land sector, and identify areas that require further attention.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe LGAF process is guided by a framework of 21 land governance indicators in the 5 key areas listed above, each divided into 3-4 
defaultdimensions for which rankings are assigned by expert panels based on pre-coded answers (on a scale from A to D) that draw on global experience. Through a consensual and participatory assessment by local experts of this core set of indicators, the LGAF serv
defaultes to map out key information on land governance and define actionable paths for policy interventions, all in a contextualized and country-driven manner. Implementation takes place in a number of discrete steps that are overseen by a local coordinator, a w
defaultell-respected and impartial person with extensive knowledge of the sector.
default&#xa0;
defaultI would recommend that the 
defaultScottish Affairs Committee
default commissions a review of Scotland’s current land governance through the LGAF. This will then guide the most appropriate policy 
defaultinterventions. 
